The central routines XSA0X and XSB0X
For creating a regularly re’¼üned mesh and allocating all arrays on the workspace vector the user may invoke the subprograms XSA0X, for triangular meshes and XSB0X for quadrilaterals. The second letter X denotes that these routines again only invoke the X-routines XSA0, XSB0, XS2M, and XS2V.
All elements are subdivided into four subelements. For triangular elements, for each edge an interior point is determined by the subdivision programs S2DI, for interior edges, and S2DB, on the boundary. This new point, frequently the midpoint of the edge becomes a new vertex in the re’¼üned mesh. The three new points are connnected by lines what divides the triangle into four subelements. The interior element is given the former number of the element, the other three elements obtain the new numbers NEL+1, NEL+2, and NEL+3. Then NEL is increased by 3. New vertices obtain new numbers, starting at NVT+1, old vertices keep their numbers.
Similarly, for quadrilaterals, all four edges are subdivided and connected. The subelement containing the ŌĆØ’¼ürstŌĆØ vertex of the original element keeps the old number, the other three subelements are enumerated as described above. The old vertices keep their number, then the new vertices on edges of the old subdivision and, ’¼ünally, the new interior vertices are enumerated. In order to modify the mesh the user may provide subprograms S2DI and S2DB by himself.

